How Charisma Affects Leadership

Charisma, such a mysterious word. Its that something that we feel someone has, but cant quite put a finger on it. Its a quality that persuades us to believe and follow what were being told. This word often bears a positive connotation. We believe that its a quality that a leader must have to command respect and obedience. But charisma isnt always so positive. While it can evoke respect from others, it can also create fear among subjects. And unfortunately, its the latter that most destructive leaders in history have used charisma for. But when put in the hands of a good leader, it can be used to motivate and persuade a team to give out the best they can. This point is best illustrated by a quick case study about how charisma works by John Antonakis, a professor at the University of Lausanne in Switzerland. ( The editor-in-chief for The Leadership Quarterly has also given a Ted Talk about the same topic). In Johns experiment, he took a group of mail sorting workers during the holidays who would sort Santa letters from kids, and split them into three groups:

  1. The workers in the first group were given the same fixed wage, based on the number of hours worked + a normal, non-charismatic speech
  2. The second group of workers was given the same fixed wage, based on the number of hours worked + an incentive when they hit or exceed a certain number of envelopes sorted + a normal, non-charismatic speech
  3. The last group were given the same fixed wage, based on the number of hours worked with no incentives or bonus pay + a tailored charismatic speech about what and why they were doing
The final result wasnt very surprising. As expected, the second had the most productivity with a 20% increase in their output, due to the potential to earn more. But what was more unexpected was the gap between the first and the third group. Group 3 had an 18% boost in their productivity than Group 1. Yet, the only thing different in their working condition was the speech they heard before completing the task. This experiment has how charisma can persuade people to do what theyre being to do, regardless of the compensation theyll get. As a business leader, the only takeaway you can get from here is, if you want an increase in your teams productivity, be a charismatic leader who can motivate your team to exceed their limits.
